  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions can be traced through several key developments:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal money concealment practices existed historically\n- Initial anti-money laundering (AML) efforts emerged in response to organized crime\n\n2. United States Developments:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First major legislative effort to combat financial crimes\n- Required financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Established reporting requirements for suspicious financial activities\n\n3. International Milestones:\n- 1988 UN Vienna Convention - Criminalized drug trafficking proceeds\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Developed international standards for combating money laundering\n\n4. Post-9/11 Regulations:\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) significantly expanded AML requirements\n- Enhanced financial monitoring and reporting mechanisms\n- Increased focus on terrorism financing prevention\n\n5. Global Regulatory Expansion:\n- Increased international cooperation\n- More comprehensive legal frameworks\n- Stricter penalties for non-compliance\n- Enhanced cross-border information sharing\n\n6. Technological Adaptations:\n- Regulations addressing digital currencies\n- Cybercrime-related money laundering provisions\n- Updated compliance mechanisms for emerging financial technologies\n\nThe legal landscape continues evolving to address increasingly sophisticated financial crime strategies.",
